english:
  title: A Record of the New Tower at the Public Hall of Gokju
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Gokju is a district in the remote reaches of the western sea, with Gyoje to its east and Pyongyang to its north. High mountains and clear waters surround a level plain where the district seat stands. The public hall lies near the northern edge, encircled by common dwellings, leaving visitors with nowhere to ascend and nothing to behold—as if trapped in a well. Governor Yun Sangbal lamented this state of affairs and set about felling trees and clearing brush, raising a small pavilion. When his term ended and Governor Kim arrived to succeed him, he declared, "Yun did not lack the ability; he merely waited for me." With his officers, Kim expanded the grounds further, gathering timber from the mountains and firing tiles in the fields. Within two months, the axes and chisels had completed their work.

    Then Kim sent his guest, Attendant Seo Yunmyeong, to request this record. I said: "Our nation's territory is bounded by three great seas, with the northern reaches touching the Long White Mountains. Along the coastal regions, towers and pavilions once gleamed in splendor, and travelers gazed upon one another's banners. Entertainment and music filled all four seasons without ceasing, as unchanging as a single day across centuries. Yet since the rise of sea pirates, year after year and month after month have brought increasing turmoil. Beacon fires burn through day and night, and armor knows neither summer nor winter. The coastal lands have become mere bone yards, overgrown with desolate weeds. What need speak of towers and pavilions? Only crumbling mounds remain, where foxes and rabbits roam, moving all who pass to tears.

    But Gokju lies some three hundred li north of the capital, far distant from the sea. Its people know nothing of beacon fires. They fill their bellies at dawn and dusk, sow and reap with the seasons, and know no other cares. Thus a governor there need not labor much to achieve much—this is clear. How much more so when one rules with compassion and acts with righteousness? The people find ease readily, and order takes hold readily. Can another be found like Governor Kim? That this new tower should arise is assuredly certain.

    A governor's duty is to cherish his people. When the people find peace, this suffices. Peace comes through their reverence of superiors, which requires diligent adherence to law and courteous treatment of all. Governor Kim knows what is urgent. His name is Seungwi, and he holds the rank of the third order. Observe this undertaking, and you shall know the man.

    Governor Yun was once my student, and Attendant Seo is the nephew of my late wife's family. Thus I did not refuse, but set down this brief account.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Gokju (谷州) refers to Goksan County in Hwanghae Province, in present-day North Korea.
  - key: ''
    value: The Long White Mountains (장백산) were understood by classical Korean writers as the northern boundary of the Korean peninsula.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to sea pirates reflects the historical reality of Japanese and Jurchen raids that plagued Korean coastal regions, particularly during the late Goryeo and early Joseon periods.
  - key: ''
    value: The three ranks (三品) mentioned refers to the middle rank in the official bureaucratic hierarchy of Goryeo.
